        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>mordrakken</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Sometimes mobs are just more likely to see through even a 'successful' FD. Go to the hole. The very entrance. The elementals there often see through a successful FD. They even may con indifferent to you while you're down, but they'll still attack you. I had theorized it had something to do with slow, or them coming off a stun, or any number of other things, so I tried it a few times and it basically comes down to this guess at a theory:</P><P>Mobs over a certain level, possibly of a specific type, in a specific zone, or flagged a certain way, have a (greater?) chance to see through feign. </P><P>Our feign, being a spell, is likely set at a certain number on the roll -- meaning we are arbitrarily assigned a skill value to use when calculating 'success' or 'failure'. A critical failure means we get the 'falls down' message. However, a less critical failure may result in certain mobs being able to see through it. Monks, as they have an actual FD skill and likely do not have an arbitrary value (such as 100, perhaps, or some value based on our skill in that type of magic or our level) at higher levels have a far greater chance of successfully feigning (beyond just 'falls down'). I have noticed that my monk roommate nearly never has a mob see through feign once she's down (such as in the hole, where she commonly fights, sometimes with me), whereas I will have the problem consistantly in certain zones, against certain mobs. The vampire bats in ME tend to see through her feign, as well, leading me to believe that there is more to it than level and skill alone. This isn't due to AoE's hitting, spells landing, etc.</P><P>Added on top of this is how exactly the 'hate list' wiping actually works. I would wager that it reduces hate an amount based on the roll. Alternatively it could simply have a base chance to wipe the hate list, or a base chance to reduces hate a specific amount. Thus, you could have a 50% chance to do say, 500 points of hate reduction. Or you could have a 50% chance to completely wipe yourself from a particular mob's hate list, and so forth. However it works, repeatedly feigning does work, as either you reduce your hate enough, or you simply finally make a 'hate wipe' roll on that mob. Sometimes multiple feigns won't work to clear even a monk from the hate list even when the monk did only a few points of damage. This lends credibility to the theory that the hate list reduction, even on a successful feign is either a) variable, sometimes not being enough to remove even a few points of hate, or b) fixed, but having a chance to be or not be applied, or c) a combination of both or some alternative method.</P><P>I haven't read over monk boards about this topic, but I would wager that they have far more in depth discussions and thoughts on the matter and it would prove useful to possibly inquire as to such there.</P><P>I heartily suggest that any of you willing to take the time to do some testing try this out. Specifically the hole and ME I can vouch for mobs often seeing through my feign, but also umbral plains, and sometimes sirens grotto as well. I don't often have this problem in lower level zones or against lower level mobs (take your pick as to which it would be -- I would guess the mob is what matters, but it could be that a zone has an inherent modifier versus feign, as well).</P><P>It certainly isn't something that's 100%. For instance, the spectres in the hole almost never saw through my feign, the rock golems did periodically and the elementals commonly. This is based on impressions, so is hardly useful statistical data. I may go back and track how many times it works or such in the future for certain mob types. Who knows.</P><P> </font></td>
      </tr>
